ce:section.ce:para:
1H NMR spectroscopic studies were used to investigate hydrogen-bonding self-assembly formation between TA and urea (Fig. 1
). Upon interaction of TA molecule and urea molecule, the carboxylate proton signal of TA underwent a slight downfield shift in the NMR titration experiment, as shown in Fig. 1b, indicating the carboxylate proton was not involved in the formation of hydrogen bonds since their NMR signals showed almost no shifted [30]. In a contrast, a significant shift of the amino proton signal was observed when interacting with the TA molecule, which is demonstrated by the NMR titration experiments (Fig. 1c). The signal at δ = 5.474 ppm was attribute to the amino protons of urea molecules. Fig. 1c showed that when urea molecules were mixed with different molar ratio of TA molecules (nTA/nUrea = 1:6, 1:3, 2:3, 4:3 and 8:3) in DMSO‑d
6, the signal of 5.474 ppm will upfield shift to 5.436, 5.424, 5.412, 5.415 and 5.433 ppm with a maximum of 5.412 ppm when TA molecules were blended with 1.5 equiv of urea molecule (2:3 of molar ratio). Since TA consists of three carboxylic acid groups and urea contains two amino group, these results demonstrate TA/urea hydrogen-bonding complex formed with 1:1 binding between carboxylic and amino group as shown in Scheme 1.
